eading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":3,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":13,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes de Lisours was born about 1093, in Nottinghamshire, England, her father, William de Lisours II, was 24 and her mother, Mrs. William De Lisours, was 21. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Henry d'Alneto."},"et":{"about 1093–":"umbes 1093–Surnud","1087–Female":"1087–Surnud","1093–Female":"1093–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1110–1172":"1110–1172","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1073–Female":"1073–Surnud","about 1093":"umbes 1093","1106":"1106","1110":"1110","1087":"1087","1096":"1096","about 1110":"umbes 1110","1073":"1073","1172":"1172","1060":"1060","1093":"1093","1070":"1070","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Turvey, Bedfordshire, England":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1093–":"noin 1093–K